I have failed Calc I under a different instructor, and not from lack of trying. This instructor made all the difference. I cannot emphasize that enough.    Lectures were delivered in a straight-forward manner. No cute gimmicks or clip-art were used. No power point presentations and very few handouts, so the material on the black board could go "off script" controlled and paced out as questions came up. The lessons were on a chalkboard. New concepts were given a to-the-point introduction explaining what we're looking at today (what this concept does, how it is different from what we were doing, what we can find out now). This helped to "motivate" the lesson and take it out of the abstract, as well as connecting it to our current body of knowledge. We would then go through example problems that best explained the concepts. Clear hand writing, very little shorthand, very select short-cuts when calculating.    The instructor did a good job of monitoring the progress of the class as a whole and was able to appropriately adjust lesson plans to address issues with concepts. Still we were able to complete the intended lesson plan set out from the beginning of the semester. The tests were fair in terms of the material covered vs how recent the topic was so that very new or not-fully-discussed concepts were saved for the following exam.    Above everything, the instructor always, always, always went out of his way to make himself available for questions on the material, was patient when explaining it, and would work with you until you got it. I would see the instructor 1-3 times a week, and see tutors through the university 2-4 times a week.    This was still a struggle, but in the end, I strongly felt grades reflected my grasp of the subject and not circumstances of how the class was structured. Oddly, that has not always been the case with many classes in math.     One day of lecture was used as a review for material on upcoming exams. These gave a pointed summary of take-home points from *LECTURE* more-so than the book. Books tend to have summary's at the end of each chapter/section, but don't do the same job as an instructor explaining key points tailored to the class.    This was a model instructor, and I felt very fortunate to have taken this course.

I feel like the instructional method (for both calculus I and II) should focus more on teaching the processes for computation, such as strategies for setting up and solving integrals (which was covered to some extent), since it is such a major part of being able to solve the problems. Also, the relationships between derivatives and anti-derivatives (trig functions, speed/acceleration/distance, etc.) should be given a more graphical basis. Relating new topics to what we already know and integrating the information should be a priority. Assessments (not tests) should be done formally, not left up to the student to assess on their own, in order to judge a student's strengths and weaknesses to identify what may be causing the most difficulty, and what the student understands well. I have a hard time learning in lecture, although in all of my other classes I can sit and listen and not need to take notes and learn everything. Writing on a chalk or whiteboard is ineffective in my opinion as compared to presenting the problem already written out and explaining what problem solving strategies to use to get from one step to the other (similarly to what is done in a textbook - since what the teacher does is basically explain what is in the book, it would be the same as showing what is in the book, and explaining it instead of writing what is in the book, doing all of the computation steps and in my opinion wasting time). Showing how to identify what method to use to solve a problem should be the primary goal of the class (problem solving techniques) and teaching those methods more instead of computation should be the focus. I know that the integral of 1/x^2 + 1 is arctan(x), but I couldn't tell you why, or even what arctan *is* although I could know that it is cos/sin but where does it come from? I can't learn under the current system; I would learn much better with one on one instruction, since I always have questions but don't want to use time that is spent on going through examples, bc if others can learn that way, I don't want to slow them down. I feel like the method I described, if it were adopted, or something similar were incorporated, would be more similar to that 1:1 learning and more students would ask more questions and everyone would learn more and understand better.

The teacher did a really great job of helping us to learn/discover on our own. In class, he would spend some time each day talking about applications of what we were learning -- cool uses for a logarithmic spiral, what a cardioid is, other cool stuff. We also had a weekly reading to do that talked about more cool things, for example, Hotel Infinity, how e^x relates so much to natural exponential growth of things, and so forth.   He also made us read in the book the stuff we were going to talk about in class -- BEFORE class started. I thought that was pretty important. We're doing the same thing in my Linear Algebra math class right now, and it's still helpful. It's good because when you read it the first time, you get kind of a feel for what you're going to talk about, and you start to understand the concepts a little bit. Then in class the teacher teaches about it and can focus on explaining the really difficult or interesting parts, and can answer specific questions of the students, rather than spoon-feeding every little detail to us.

I generally felt that Calculus I was a bland class that was intended for such a wide variety of audiences that it lost most if not all appeal.  I thought the curriculum was illogical and didn't produce the best possible results, and this motivated me to take Calculus III at a different school, particularly after Calculus II proved similar.

I know that the University of Michigan Math Department prides itself in its small entry-level class sizes, but I found that the way it is taught here is not conducive to a thorough understanding of topics and is not productive nor realistic. For example, we had weekly group homework activities due. Not only was it very difficult to coordinate 4 or 5 peoples' schedules, but there were also countless problems with people not showing up, not putting any effort into their portion of the project or not being of any help in the group setting. Also, when it came to these assigned problems I found that some were so contorted and contrived that the concepts were all lost. Not to mention that the problems were so difficult that most of the time groups could not even get through the majority of it--but there was little motivation to because the assignments didn't count toward your grade. I think the idea of a group of students working together and teaching one another is a fantastic idealization to helping everyone better understand material, but in actuality either one person did the entire thing themselves or no one understood it at all. I studied very hard for this class though, and later for Calculus II, and was quite successful. But neither of my GSIs particularly contributed to my success, nor did the group work. I love this university and I honestly enjoy math, and I am good at math, but I think that the department is kidding themselves sometimes, and that they need to work harder to standardize the way that GSIs teach and they need to reassess what will really help the students learn.

Q7FUS: The professor moved through the material way faster than most of the class could handle. When this was pointed out to him he didn't change anything. My TA was not any better and often messed up the problems he did on the board and couldn't solve them any better than we could. I did not want to have to struggle through more Calculus classes so I changed my major and decided to give up on the class and calculus in general.
The math learning center was crucial to my success in calculus at uc. The availabilty of the people and level of expertise at which it was run helped me a lot.

The professor tended to over complicate simple concepts like a line or what a derivative was. Every week we had written homeworks due that were extremely difficult and many times the grad students that were tutors couldn't solve them. I had Calc 1 in high school so I lucky enough to already know many of the topics but several other students struggled significantly. I continued in calc because I enjoy math but this experience was not a very good one.

I took Calculus 1 in my first quarter as a college student. I had previously taken Calculus in High School and received all A's; however, I did not take the AP test to receive credit for college. Calculus in college moves entirely took quickly and the teaching was horrible. I never understood the lectures, the professor was a complete scatter brain and once said to me, "What's the point in getting it wrong when you can get it right?" when I simply asked him a question. I was not pleased with Calculus 1. The only was I succeeded was because of my previous Calculus knowledge and extra work with the TA. I continued on to Calculus 2 and 3, simply because I was not going to change my major because of Calculus; however, I am now finding difficulties in Differential Equations because my background from Calculus 1 and 2 is so poor.
In my case, it was a poor course design, as well as being taught by grad students, as opposed to Professors.

The homework assignments were literally impossible because it would take one hour to complete one questions for the PROFESSOR.  The class pace was too fast and when asking questions the responses from the professor would be vague, overly complex, or the professor would make too many mistakes in his explanation.
Well, I'd already taken calculus in high school and so essentially took a more focused calculus class at my college. So, it was all pretty good.
No thanks.
I thought it was a good base course for the further development of my mathematical skills.
The homework was too hard for what we were doing, it was above a calc 4 level

I took Advanced Placement Calculus (AB) in high school, so it was much of a review for me in my college courses. Since I understood things very well the second time around, I enjoyed the class a lot more than if it had been extremely challenging.
The teaching in Calculus I was great, and the TAs were very knowledgeable and helpful. I think that having people who can really help when you are stuck on a concept or a problem is very important.

Q5FUS_NeverIntended: I never intended to take Calculus II.
Q7FUS: After taking Calculus I, I realized that I could have worked much harder when I took it. I did not complete all of the homework on time or attentively attend every class. Looking back now and knowing what I know now, I would have definitely applied myself more.

The class was not interactive and was primarily conceptual.Homework problems did not correlate with class lessons and exams were a complete level above all class or homework. This class assumed previous calculus and mandatory independent learning. Compared to calculus 2 in a different department, this class was horrible and the amount learned was minimal with 4 times more work.

Calculus 1 was mostly a review from high school for me. I'm definitely glad I retook it though, because it helped a lot for calc 2. I had a lot of tutoring available for me. The most helpful was the tutor that came to the dorms for homework help a couple nights a week.
Webassign really helped me in continuing to take calculus because it was an easy way to get instant feedback and in some cases, clear instruction (via videos/tutorialis).

What helped me succeed and therefore want to continue taking calculus:  Professor used examples in lectures and a good teacher in general  Homework was online with multiple submissions (we could try for the right answer more than once), instant feedback on each question, often online-walkthroughs of the problems (videos or step-by-step instructions of similar problems)  Math tutoring available on campus 6 days a week, open 12 hours a day Mon-Thur  Professor and teaching assistant (TA) available to ask questions, office hours every week  Class format with lectures (taught by professor) and quiz sections (taught by TA, who is a grad student)  Past midterms and finals online along with solutions to help study for exams
I need it for my major

On my first ever college exam, a Calculus I exam, there was this really long and complicated problem that everyone in the class had trouble with. After the exam I had though I had bombed the test because I probably had made some silly error on that question and most likely another. I was extremely happy when the test came back and I had got 100%.
